  <discussion>Schistidium atrichum is the smallest North American species in the genus.  Along with the small size of its leaves, stems, and capsules, the usual lack of awns on vegetative leaves and its habit of forming small, often flat cushions help to distinguish it.  S. Flowers (1973) noted strong similarities between S. atrichum and S. dupretii, but the larger size and the consistently ribbed capsules separate S. dupretii.</discussion>
